Magnetic properties of Fe3O4, Fe3O4/Cdots 50 %, and Fe3O4/Cdots 70 % were shown as M−H curves in Fig. 11
                           . The sigmoid and narrow curve of all samples show nearly superparamagnetic that make it vulnerable to applied magnetic field [32,45]. The saturation magnetization (Ms
                           ) is the highest magnetization achieved after all magnetic moments are aligned. The Ms
                            of Fe3O4, Fe3O4/Cdots 50 %, and Fe3O4/Cdots 70 % are 54.2, 38.3 emu/g, and 34.3 emu/g, respectively. The Ms
                            proportionally decreases, corresponds to increasing Cdots concentration, as shown in Table 3
                           . Cdots as non-magnetic material cause decreasing magnetic moment per unit mass of nanocomposites and inhibit the switching of magnetic moment that will affect the magnetic properties [43,63]. Besides, adding Cdots might affect the susceptibility of nanocomposites that representing magnetic respons material. Decreasing magnetization saturation strengthened that Cdots were successfully attached on the surface of magnetite, supporting the above characteristic. However, Fe3O4/Cdots have good magnetic properties that can be remote by applied magnetic field. Fe3O4/Cdots 70 % nanocomposite (lowest Ms
                           ) easy separated in aqueous environment in short time. This indicate that Fe3O4/Cdots nanocomposites were potential as easy controllable, reusable, and targeting material. On the other hand, the coercivity (Hc
                           ) is not significant different after the addition of Cdots, which is due to almost similar size of nanoparticles.
